{"source_key":"sha256-57a0ef58ecdd57e62937c2289b37339b","record_index":1752,"record_hash":"sha256:f5847d1b875f5dd9cc41643a400236910e4c4143c50616c98b6db45422e94596","timestamp":"2026-05-26T13:12:18.738Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"{\"previous_status\":{\"completed\":\"**Findings**\\n\\n1. [P1] Promotion fails when the target branch was absent in the previous snapshot.\\n[read.rs]([REDACTED:path]) returns false unless `previous_commit_ids_for_branch(...)` finds the branch. That misses the “started with dirty files, then branch appears/gets committed next turn” case, especially with multiple current branches where the target-appearance fallback is intentionally not specific enough.\\nSuggested action: treat “branch not present previously” as an empty previous commit set, and add a regression where previous env has dirty files but no branches, current env has two branches, and only one new commit contains the dirty path.\\n\\n2. [P1] The main positive promotion test can pass without promotion logic.\\n[tests.rs]([REDACTED:path]) uses a targetless first turn and a specific target on the second turn, so [read.rs]([REDACTED:path]) can associate it via “target appeared after targetless turn” even if `environment_promotes_worktree_to_target` is broken.\\nSuggested action: make the first turn already observe the target, or make the second turn observe multiple targets, so only file promotion can make the session match.\\n\\n3. [P2] Raw commit file paths are now stored in synced GitMeta without a projection privacy regression.\\n[environment.rs]([REDACTED:path]) serializes `CommitSnapshot.files`, and [write.rs]([REDACTED:path]) stores that environment in turn detail. Current public projection structs do not expose environment, but the privacy test at [tests.rs]([REDACTED:path]) only guards tool payload paths.\\nSuggested action: add a projection test with environment worktree/commit files like `privat